    "slug": "ebitda-per-cycle-how-technology-reduces-ivfs-marginal-cost-of-scaling",
    "title": "EBITDA per Cycle: How Technology Reduces IVF’s Marginal Cost of Scaling",
    "excerpt": "For investors, the promise of IVF is high margins. The reality of scaling it has been a high marginal cost. We're changing that calculus in Eastern India. The conventional wisdom i...",
    "html": "<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*pdjq_YmZ-2B8W-ufopKavQ.png\"></figure><p>For investors, the promise of IVF is high margins. The reality of scaling it has been a high marginal cost. We're changing that calculus in Eastern India.</p>\n<p>The conventional wisdom in fertility investing is simple: a mature, well-run IVF clinic should deliver 35-45% EBITDA margins. The unspoken truth is that these margins compress dramatically when you try to scale beyond a flagship location.</p>\n<p>The hub-and-spoke model that defined the first wave of Indian fertility chains- Nova, Birla, Indira- runs into a critical bottleneck: the marginal cost of adding a new patient cycle does not fall. It often rises.</p>\n<p>Why? Because scaling traditionally meant replicating expensive, people-intensive infrastructure. A new city required a new lab, a new team of embryologists (a scarce resource), and a new local marketing spend to build trust from zero. The unit economics were merely duplicated, not optimised.</p>\n<h4><strong>The Santaan Thesis: Technology as a Marginal Cost Lever</strong></h4>\n<p>Our investment thesis at Santaan is built on inverting this problem. We don't see technology as just a clinical tool; we see it as the primary lever to reduce the marginal cost per cycle as we scale across Eastern India's high-demand, low-supply markets.</p>\n<p><strong>Let's break down the components of a cycle's cost and where technology intervenes:</strong></p>\n<p><strong>1. Patient Acquisition Cost (PAC): The Trust Deficit</strong></p>\n<p>In non-metro Eastern India, PAC isn't about Google Ads bids. It's about overcoming a profound trust deficit in a deeply private health matter. Traditional chains use broad branding; we use targeted, empathetic content and a telemedicine-first funnel.</p>\n<p><strong>• Telemedicine Triage:</strong> 60% of initial consultations happen virtually. This drastically reduces the 'friction' for a first touchpoint, expanding our catchment area without physical footprint costs.</p>\n<p><strong>• Content-Driven Trust:</strong> Our regional-language educational platforms build credibility before a marketing rupee is spent. This converts at a higher rate and lower cost than performance marketing.</p>\n<p><strong>• Community Health Worker Network:</strong> A tech-enabled network of local advocates provides warm introductions, turning high-cost cold acquisition into lower-cost warm handoffs.</p>\n<p><strong>Result:</strong> Our PAC in Odisha is 28% lower than the industry average for a new tier-2 clinic, and this gap widens as our content library and community reputation compound.</p>\n<p><strong>2. Clinical Protocol &amp; Lab Efficiency: The AI Multiplier</strong></p>\n<p>The single largest variable cost in an IVF cycle is the embryologist's time and expertise. Standardisation is elusive.</p>\n<p><strong>• AI-Driven Embryo Selection:</strong> Our platform uses AI to grade embryos. This doesn't replace the embryologist but augments them, allowing one senior embryologist at our Bhubaneswar hub to oversee quality for multiple spoke centres via digital dashboards. It improves consistency and outcomes while stretching a scarce resource.</p>\n<p><strong>• Centralised Lab Model:</strong> Complex procedures remain at our central, accredited lab in Bhubaneswar. Spoke centres handle consultations, monitoring, and simpler procedures. This avoids the ₹2-3 Cr capital outlay and operational headache of building a Grade-A lab in every city.</p>\n<p><strong>• Protocols-as-Software:</strong> Treatment protocols are embedded in our clinical workflow software, minimising variance and training time for new clinicians.</p>\n<p><strong>Result:</strong> Cost per cycle from a lab perspective drops by an estimated 18-22% in our spoke model versus a full, independent clinic.</p>\n<p><strong>3. Overhead &amp; Management: The Platform Advantage</strong></p>\n<p>Each new clinic isn't a new P&amp;L silo. It's a node on a platform.</p>\n<p>• Unified EMR &amp; Analytics: Patient data from all touchpoints feeds a central system, enabling predictive analytics for cycle planning and inventory management.</p>\n<p>• Centralised Admin Functions: Billing, supplier management, and accreditation compliance are managed centrally, eliminating redundant roles at each location.</p>\n<h4><strong>The EBITDA Chain in Action</strong></h4>\n<p>This is not theoretical. Our model projects that while our first clinic will hit a 40% EBITDA margin at maturity, our fifth clinic will reach that margin 40% faster, because the marginal cost of adding it is subsidised by the existing tech and trust infrastructure.</p>\n<p>The 'platform S-curve' finally applies to fertility care. The high fixed cost of building the tech stack and brand trust is amortised over an expanding base of cycles and locations, making each incremental cycle more profitable than the last.</p>\n<p><strong>The Eastern India Multiplier</strong></p>\n<p>This model only works because of the specific geography we chose. Eastern India's underpenetration means we are not competing on price in a crowded metro market. We are building the only organised, tech-enabled platform in a region serving 250 million people. The demand is latent and massive; our cost structure allows us to meet it profitably at price points the market can bear.</p>\n<p>The 2021 ART Act provides regulatory clarity. The demographic need provides the demand. Our technology-first, empathy-driven model provides the path to scale with robust, defensible unit economics.</p>\n<p>For the investor, the question shifts from 'Can this clinic be profitable?' to 'How fast can this platform replicate its economics across an entire region?' That is the new math of fertility investing.</p>\n<p>The future of scalable, ethical fertility care isn't in building more expensive clinics. It's in building a smarter platform. The margin is in the technology.</p>\n<p><strong>Connect With Us</strong></p>\n<p>For Clinicians: Stay ahead of the technology curve. Join our digital health network to access real-time AI benchmarks and advanced diagnostic support for your complex cases.</p>\n<p>👉 Contact our Clinical Relations Team</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://santaan.in/contact-us\">https://www.google.com/search?q=https://santaan.in/contact-us</a></p>\n<p><strong>Technical Metadata</strong></p>",
